\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
My Thesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Tomomi Sunayama
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Exploring new diagnostics for the internal structure of clusters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Galaxy clusters are the most massive objects in the Universe, which provides
 extremely dense environments to galaxies and subhalos in those clusters.
 Under such environments, galaxy evolution is strongly affected by a strong
 tidal field such as ram-pressure stripping, 
\color red
galaxy harrasment
\color inherit
, and tidal compression.
 Among all those mechanisms, ram-pressure stripping is considered the most
 efficient mechanism under the massive cluster environments, because the
 ram-pressure stripping becomes efficient when the galaxies move relatively
 fast [cite???].
 The ram-pressure stripping removes gas from the galaxies, quenches their
 star-formation, and is considered to transform their morphologies (from
 spiral to disk) and colors (from blue to red).
 Observational evidences show that many spiral galaxies in the clusters
 have truncated gas and deficient in HI gas [cite:xxx].
 A similar phenomenon is expected for subhalos in the clusters.
 It is theoretically predicted that the strong tidal field strips the dark
 matters from the subhalos and trucates their radius.
 Through the lensing studies, the truncation of the subhalos are observationally
 confirmed; Ref.
 Natarajan [xxx] shows a mass distribution for the galaxies inside the clusters
 is tidally tructaed compared to the similar field galaxies.
 In addition to the truncation radius, Ref.xxx [Subaru] shows that the subhalo
 masses and mass-to-light ratios depend on the distance from the cluster
 center such that those properties decrease toward the cluster center.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though the strong tidal field is important for galaxy evolution as
 well as halo formation in the clusters, the studies using simulations show
 that the way tidal field acts on galaxies is different from the way it
 acts on halos; the tidal field primarily strips the outer material from
 the halos.
 Since galaxies tend to exist at the center of the halos, the galaxies may
 be less affected by the tidal field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Tidal stripping in cluster environments - what is expected theoretically
 and what is seen observationally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
** Tidal stripping of cluster galaxies a la Jeff Kenney 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
** Tidal stripping of cluster galaxies from lensing studies (PN 2009, comparison
 with simulations with Springel -- 2 papers) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Need to introduce the effect of assembly bias and its role in where galaxies
 end up radially in the cluster 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare simulations with observations of samples and go beyond individual
 objects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summary previous work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Paraphrase More et al.
 papers and their results]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clusters of galaxies are the most massive gravitationally bound objects
 in the Universe, which provide extreme environments for galaxies orbiting
 inside of the clusters.
 Tidal forces are stronger in cluster environments, due to a denser environmnt
 than galaxy groups.
 Tidal stripping is an important physical process for halo formation as
 well as galaxy formation.
 In simulations, tidal forces cause mass stripping, tidal heating, and disruptio
n of subhalos inside the host halos of the clusters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subhalos which are accreted ealier experience more tidal stripping and therefore
 lose more masses.
 Numerous studies [cite:xxx] show that those subhalos tend to have a more
 centrally concentrated radial distribution than the subhalos accreted later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*mention the difference between the effect of tidal stripping for subhalos
 and galaxies that tidal stripping tend to remove the outer material which
 is less gravitationally bound and the effect of tidal stripping for galaxies
 must be less [citation:xxx]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In observations, one of the evidences of the tidal stripping is the existence
 of cD galaxies which have grown massively by accreting material from the
 surrounding satellite galaxies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*ram pressure stripping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*lensing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been numerous studies about the halo-galaxy connection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*abundance matching/age matching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*those methods preserve assembly bias 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*tension between observations and simulations: Miyatake et al.
 and More et al.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*problems/challenges: correspondence between types of galaxies and subhalos
 is not clear, mass resolution and halo definition of halos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*splashback radius: simulations/observations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*about my work: splashback halos will affect to the clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*what I do here: the effect of assembly history on internal structure of
 clusters including ejected halos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because subhalos which lost more masses due to tidal stripping are the ones
 accreted earlier, they tend to exist closer to the center of the clusters
 (vdB: Since subhaloes that were accreted earlier have experienced more
 tidal stripping, subh aloes that have lost a larger fraction of their mass
 at infall are on more bound orbits.).
 [want to say: tidal stripping is secondary effect/probe for assembly history/ag
e of subhalos->but tidal stripping gives a physical effect to subhalos and
 possibly provide observables...even though age is not...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methods & Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Bolshoi simulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolshoi_11"

\end_inset

 which were run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov_etal97,gottloeber_klypin08"

\end_inset

 assuming a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with density parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

, giving a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos and subhalos are identified using the 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 phase-space, temporal halo finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar"

\end_inset

 and merger trees are constructed using the 
\family typewriter
CONSISTENT TREES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar_trees"

\end_inset


\family default
  procedures
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catalogues used in this paper are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, we use the virial masses and maximum circular velocities
 (tagged 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
mvir
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
vmax
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) directly from the halo catalogues.
 The 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 halo finder computes halo masses based on spherical overdensities using
 a threshold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The halo mass and velocity functions start to show incompleteness at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200$
\end_inset

 particles) for the Bolshoi simulation.
 Below those masses, the halo mass distributions show unphysical drop-offs
 indicating incomplete mass resolution.
 Therefore, we only slect subhalos whose masses at accretion are greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the standard classification of halos into host halos (not
 within the virial radius of a more massive halo) and subhalos (within the
 virial radius of a more massive halo), we further classify host halos into
 ejected and non-ejected halos.
 Ejected halos, also referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backsplash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 halos, are host halos whose main progenitor was classified, at some point
 in its merger tree history, as a subhalo.
 As we discuss below, these ejected halos have very different clustering
 properties compared to their non-ejected counterparts.
 The ejected fraction for the Bolshoi simulation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15.8\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{11}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

, and drops to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim6.3\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present our primary results from the simulations to
 see the segregation of the subhalos due to tidal stripping and dynamical
 friction.
 We begin in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:z_acc"

\end_inset

 by describing the correlation between the redshift at accretion 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the virial mass of subhalos at present and at accretion respectively.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:radial_dist"

\end_inset

, we show the radial distribution of subhalos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:correlation_fn"

\end_inset

, we show the correlation function of subhalos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 in real and redshift spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Correlation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:z_acc"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tidal stripping is a phenomenon that the subhalos experience mass loss due
 to tidal forces of their host halos.
 The tidal radius, which is a radius that binding energy of DM particles
 in the subhalos and tidal force are in equal, is roughly proportional to
 
\begin_inset Formula $(M_{{\rm sub}}/M_{{\rm host}})^{1/2}R$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm host}}$
\end_inset

 are the virial mass of subhalos and host halos respectively and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the distance between the subhalos and the host halos.
 As a general trend, subhalos with low concentration tend to be disrupted
 more easily (cite:xxx).
 [Also, add more explanation from Frank's textbook, may mention a little
 bit about dynamical friction too]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subhalo property 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 indicates the amount of mass loss after subhalos are accreted by their
 host halos due to tidal stripping.
 The question is how this property 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 correlates with other subhalo properties such as the redshift at accretion
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 One of the motivation we want to know the correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is because 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is used in the age-matching technique to assign color to those subhalos,
 which enables us to connect simulations and observations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:correlation_z"

\end_inset

 shows correlation of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 as well as with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are tightly correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is expected, because the subhalos who are accreted earlier must be
 striped more mass due to tidal stripping.
 Quantitatively, the cross correlation coefficients for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is xxx, while it is xxx for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 As is clear from the figures, the change in halo mass is larger than the
 change in the maximum circular velocity.
 This is mostly because approximately the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\propto M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}$
\end_inset

 holds.
 Applying this scaling relation and converting 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\color red
still steeper (or same
\color inherit
) than the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 with scatter of xxx.
 Those results are consistent with the results in Ref.
 xxx [vdB, Figure 5].
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\propto M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 By converting the change in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 to scale with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, the results for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are consistent each other.
 
\color red
This actually throws some doubt on the picture that tidal stripping removes
 the mass of the subhalos from their outer regions and therefore the change
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 is smaller.
 (This statement is not made in any references for subhalos...Read vdB's potential
 depth paper and Arthur's paper to confirm the picture, at least this says
 that tidal stripping strip the matter not only from outer regions...)
\end_layout

