\begin_layout Subsection
Radial distribution of subhalos 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:radial_dist"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present our primary results for the radial distribution
 of subhalos in the cluster-sized host halos (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm host}}>10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{{\rm \odot}}}$
\end_inset

) as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 In order to study the dependence of the radial distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, we split subhalos into three bins: 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}>10^{-0.5}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}=[10^{-1},10^{-0.5}]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}<10^{-1}$
\end_inset

 (
\color red
show the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset


\color inherit
?).
 Then, we compute the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for the subhalos from the center of their host halos, and bin those subhalos
 into a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $r/R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 bins where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the virial radius of the host halos.
 The result is shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_real"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_real"

\end_inset

 indicates that subhalos which lose more masses tend to exist closer to
 the center of their host halos.
 In other words, those subhalos are on more bound orbits, which is consistent
 with the result in Ref.
 xxx[Frank's paper Figure 5].
 There are two possible reasons why the subhalos which experience more mass
 loss are closer to the center.
 One is due to dynamical friction and the other is due to hierarchical structure
 formation of halos (called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inside-out assembly of halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Ref.
 xxx).
 Ref.
 xxx computed the expected radial distribution of subhalos as a function
 of the redshifts at accretion without dynamical friction and showed that
 the latter scenario is more plausible.
 In other words, the reason the subhalos which lost more mass are closer
 to the center is because those subhalos are accreted earlier and therefore
 the virial radius of the host halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 was also smaller.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_M14_radial.pdf
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:radial_real"

\end_inset

Radial distribution of subhalos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo masses at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

 and at accretion respectively.
 Having smaller ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 implies that subhalos lost more masses due to tidal stripping, and those
 subhalos whose masses are more stripped tend to be closer to the center
 of the host halo.
 Note that histograms are normalized.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*plot the scatter between z_acc and r/Rvir as a function of m/m_acc and
 m_acc/M0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we check the radial distribution in redshift-space as well as the
 projected distance.
 This is because we cannot measure the radial distribution in real-space
 from observations.
 So, we either need to compute the radial distribution in redshift-space
 using the spectroscopic redshifts or the projected distance from angular
 diameter distances.
 The effect of redshift-space distortions (often called the Finger-of-God
 (FoG) effect) for the subhalos in the cluster-sized host halos must be
 significant, because the velocity dispersions for galaxies in clusters
 are roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $1000{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

.
 It implies that the radial distribution in redshift-space can be extended
 more than 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (i.e., roughly ten times larger than the virial radius of the host halos
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

).
 Instead of measuring the radial distribution in redshift-space, using the
 projected distances will not suffer from the FoG effect; 
\color red
however, the projected distances are the function of radial distances and
 the angle between the center of host halos and the subhalos, and this angle-dep
endence will mix up the distribution
\color inherit
.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_redshift"

\end_inset

 shows the radial distribution of the subhalos in redshift-space, which
 actually extends to almost 14 times of the virial radius of their host
 halos, while the right panel shows the distribution of the projected distances.
 Both the effect of redshift-space distortions and projecting the radial
 distances make the dependence of radial distribution on 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 weakened; however, projecting the radial distances seems favored to see
 the dependence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_redshift"

\end_inset

, the clear signal of segregation shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_real"

\end_inset

 is smeared out; however, the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}<10^{-1}$
\end_inset

 exist outer region compared to the rest of the subhalos both in redshift-space
 and for projected distance.
 This implies that it is possible to detect this segregation from observation
 using the age-matching technique.
\end_layout

