\begin_layout Subsection
Small-scale clusterings in real and redshift spaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:correlation_fn"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we select subhalos in the same manner as in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:radial_dist"

\end_inset

 based on 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and compute the two-point correlation function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(r)$
\end_inset

.
 In all that follows, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{sub,sub}$
\end_inset

 to denote the auto-correlation of the subhalos and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{mm}$
\end_inset

 to denote the matter auto-correlation.
 The advantage of using the correlation functions is that it does not require
 to find the center of the clusters and to define the virial radius of the
 host halos 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

.
 The disadvantage is that the effect on the radial distribution will be
 smeared out more by not scaling with respect to the virial radius of the
 host halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:auto-sub_real"

\end_inset

 shows the auto-correlation functions of the subhalos split by 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 in real-space, and the right panel shows the ratio of the auto-correlation
 functions between the subhalos and matter.
 As expected, the clustering signal of those subhalos show different scale-depen
dence; the subhalos which lose more masses (i.e., accreted earlier) tend to
 cluster at the center, while the subhalos which are accreted later cluster
 more strongly at 
\begin_inset Formula $r>1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we computed the correlation functions in redshift-space.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:auto_sub-redshift"

\end_inset

 shows the monopole term of the subhalo auto-correlation functions, while
 the right panel shows the quadrupole terms.
 For the monopole terms, the segregation signal is completely smeared out
 and the correlation functions for each sample is almost indistinguishable;
 however, the quadrupole term shows different scale-dependence for each
 sample more clearly.
\end_layout

